BASH - new commands

man - manpage ids according to types of manuals

	1  Program section
	2  Syscall section
	3  Library section
	4  Device section
	5  File format section
	6  Games section
	7  Misc section
	8  Admin section
	9  Kernel section
	l  Local section
	n  New section
	tcl  Tcl section
	o  Old section

	man -k - seach the man pages

pwd - print working directory

	pwd -P - print physical location in case the current
			 working directory is accessed via a symlink
	pwd -L - print full path even if CWD is actually a symlink

pwdx - print process working directory
	pwdx 3315
	3315: /home/cvetomir

lsof -i - a utility that displays information about open file descriptors
	- print open files and processes that use them

	lsof -i
	lsof -i :3306 - print ports and processes that use them
	lsof -u username - return file descriptors opened by a certain user
	lsof -u^username - return file descriptors except by those opened by a certain user
	lsof -i -n -P

	List Unix-domain sockets:
	lsof -U

lsipc - list IPC

ls

	ls -F - display files superceded by a special symbol indexing their type
	* - executable
	/ - directory

lsinitrd - get initrd content

ipcs - retrieve information for currently running interprocess communications on the system

	ipcs -s - retrieve semaphore arrays setup
	ipcs -m - shared memory segments
	ipcs -q - message queues
	ipcs -s - semaphore arrays
	ipcs -a - all (this is the default)

	Additional options for the output format:

	-t     time
	-p     pid
	-c     creator
	-l 	   limits
	-u     summary

pmap - print the memory map of an object

symlink - utility to maintain symlinks

lshw - list hardware - displays information about the hardware on the system

hwloc - GUI tool for hardware inspection

lshal - show a list of the devices and their properties

systool - view system device information by bus, class and topology as read from sysfs

cpupower - get cpu performance info

lscpu - show information about CPUs

cpu-checker - Debian package of tools for checking if KVM
			  would run on the processor.

	Contains:
	kvm-ok
	check-bios-nx

mpstat - show information about a multithreaded processor

vmstat - display virtual memory statistics

		vmstat --forks - display the number of forks

free

	free -l - add high and low level sections to the output.
			  "low level" memory is memory that the
			  kernel can address directly and is reserved just for the kernel.

	free -c 3 -s 5 - run free three times in an interval of 5 seconds
	free -k, -g, -m - run free displaying memory in Kilobites, gigabites and megabites
	free -h - human readable format

gearman - task runner for synchronous and asynchronous tasks written in C
		  with client libraries for multiple programming languages

corosync - framework for creating clusters of Linux servers

lspci - list all PCI devises

	lspci -k - list all modules used for the PCI devices

	verbose modes:
	lspci -v
	lspci -vv
	lspci -vvv

lsmod - show kernel modules information as read from /proc/modules
		"Size" shows the size of the module, not the used memory
		"Used by" shows how much the module is used and a list of referring modules

insmod - insert a kernel module

rmmod - remove modules from the kernel

lsb_release - get distribution information

	lsb_release -a - get the name and version of current Linux distribution

lsscsi - list the connected SCSI devices

hardinfo - GUI for viewing system information (OS, hardware and partitions)

netstat - a tool used to get information about the network state

	netstat -tulnp - lists open network ports and the processes
			that own them

	-l - list only listening ports

netstat -antp | grep :3306 | wc -l - check open MySQL connections

sockstat - list information about sockets

	sockstat -l - list listening sockets
	sockstat -4 - show only sockets using IPv4

nohup - can be used to "demonize" processes - it runs them without tty output
		and immune to hangups (HUPs) - the processes are terminated after the user logs out

parallel - execute commands in parallel

apropos - search the manual page names and description

updatedb - update the database for the locale

showconsolefont - get current console font

setfont - set tty font

fc-cache - refresh system font cache

	fc-cache -f -v

df
	df -i - displays number of inodes per filesystem
	df -T - display filesystem types

du - estimate file space usage

	du -h - human readable format
	du -ah -
	du -c - show total filesize in the end
	du -hs - show disk summary
	du -d or --max-depth - check the depth of the search

ncdu - TUI which displays recursively the content of directories
	   and the file size (ncurses du)

chkconfig -  it is  used  to  manipulate the runlevel links at boot time
			 on a Red Hat system (init scripts)

	chkconfig --list | grep 3:on - shows scripts which work on runlevel 3
	chkconfig --add

	Add a service to init level:
	chkconfig --level 3 servicename on

patchk - check if the filename contains valid POSIX portable filenames

exportfs

cmp - compare two files byte by byte

cp

	cp -a - perserve file permissions, attributes and ownerships
	cp -v - verbose mode
	cp -r - copy recursively all child files and directories if a directory is passed

whereis - locate the binary, source, and manual page files for a command

		whereis ls
		ls: /bin/ls /usr/share/man/man1p/ls.1p.gz /usr/share/man/man1/ls.1.gz

brctl - ethernet bridge administrator

ebrtables - Ethernet bridge frame table administration

ethtool - control network driver and hardware settings
	ethtool -i eth0
	ethtool eth0 - check eth0 port status and see if there's an
			Ethernet link

mii-tool - ethtool is extending the mii-tool functionality

iwlwifi - suitable wifi/wi-fi driver for my Samsung laptop

	The firmware-iwlwifi package on a Debian system from a non-free repository

update-rc.d - it is used to manipulate the runlevel links at boot time
			  on a Debian system (init scripts)

ebtables - Ethernet bridge frame table administration

tcpdump

	tcpdump "cookbook" / cheatsheet:
	https://hackertarget.com/tcpdump-examples/

date - get or set the date

	to set the date:

	date 111720092015 - day, month, time, year

	Similar to strftime C function:
	http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/ctime/strftime/

	+%d+%m+%Y

		Format options 	Purpose of Option 	Output
		 +%a 	Displays Weekday name in short (like Mon, Tue, Wed) 	Thu
		 +%A 	Displays Weekday name in full short (like Monday, Tuesday) 	Thursday
		 +%b 	Displays Month name in short (like Jan, Feb, Mar ) 	Feb
		 +%B 	Displays Month name in full short (like January, February) 	February
		 +%d 	Displays Day of month (e.g., 01) 	07
		 +%D 	Displays Current Date; shown in MM/DD/YY 	02/07/13
		 +%F 	Displays Date; shown in YYYY-MM-DD 	2013-02-07
		 +%H 	Displays hour in (00..23) format 	23
		 +%I 	Displays hour (01..12) format 	11
		 +%j 	Displays day of year (001..366) 	038
		 +%m 	Displays month (01..12) 	02
		 +%M 	Displays minute (00..59) 	44
		 +%S 	Displays second (00..60) 	17
		 +%N 	Displays nanoseconds (000000000..999999999) 	573587606
		 +%T 	Displays time; shown as HH:MM:SS
				Note: Hours in 24 Format 	23:44:17
		 +%u 	Displays day of week (1..7); 1 is Monday 	4
		 +%U 	Displays week number of year, with Sunday as first day of week (00..53) 	05
		 +%Y 	Displays full year i.e. YYYY 	2013
		 +%Z 	alphabetic time zone abbreviation (e.g., EDT) 	IS

	get UTC time:
	date -u

hwclock - sets the hardware clock

	hwclock --systohc --utc

ntpdate - synchronize time with an ntp server

	ntpdate ntp.yuhu.biz

ntpq - query ntp servers

	ntpq -p

rdate - set up time

	rdate -s tick.greyware.com

tzselect - timezone select (Red Hat specific)

route - show / manipulate the IP routing table
	route -n
	route add -net 215.101.0.0/24 dev eth0
	/proc/net/route

iotop - top for disk Input-Output

iostat - display statistics about the hard disks' input/output

identify - imagemagick command line tool:

	get image exif:
	identify -format %[exif:*]

blkid - returns UUID block device IDs

login - starts a login shell

pv - monitor the progress of data through a pipe

MegaCLI - Management tool for MegaRAID controllers

	cheatsheet: http://erikimh.com/megacli-cheatsheet/

uptime - return uptime information

    uptime -p - show pretty format
    uptime -s - show since the system is up and running

arch - print system architecture

top

	Shift + h - display process threads
	e - display memory in human-readable format (change memory size unit)
	top -H -p <pid> - monitor a specific process and its threads

dmesg

	clear kernel ring buffer cache:
	dmesg -c

iotop - top for Input-Output

readlink - print value of a symbolic link or canonical file name

	readlink -f filename - get current directory + filename

dirname - get directory name in which the file resides (without filename)

-- C/C++ programming tools --

gcc - GCC compiler

	gcc --save-temp - save temporary files - output from preprocessor,
		Assembly output file etc

	Compile a file as an object:
	gcc -c main.c -o main (there's no need to use the -o option to specify the name)

	Linking object files:
	gcc main.o hello_fn.o -o hello - adding the -Wall option here is unnecessary because the source code has already been parsed and compiled.
		Linking fails if there are references that cannot be resolved.

	Object files have an .o extension. An object file is created when a source code file is compiled without creating an executable.
	On Unix systems, libraries typically have an .a extension and are usually archives.

	Link against a library(libm.a will be linked; GCC first searches for .so libraries and then for .a libs)
	gcc -Wall calc.c -lm -o calc

	include path - directories which include header files
	link path/library search path - directories which include libraries

	Directories in those paths have a precedence. Inbetween files called 'lib-a.a' the one found
	first in the link path will have precedence. (a.k.a static libraries)

	Add new search paths to the BEGINNINGS of include and link paths respectively:
	gcc -L /home/user/mylibs
	gcc -I /home/user/myheaders

	The following shell variables can be exported to add directores at the top of the include and link paths:
	C_INCLUDE_PATH
	CPLUS_INCLUDE_PATH
	LIBRARY_PATH
	LD_LIBRARY_PATH
	They can include multiple directores separated with ':'. They'll be searched from left to right.

	Force static linking:
	gcc -static

	Force the ANSI standart:
	gcc -ansi

	Compile a program to be used afterwards with the gprof profiler:
	gcc -pg execinit.c

	Macros that are defined by the compiler start with '__'.

	gcc -DMACRO=VALUE

	gcc -E test.c - similar to running the cpp command; runs the preprocessor on a source file

	gcc -O - specify optimization level (from 0 to 3; ommiting the level will run the compiler with -O0)

	Turn on loop unrolling:
	gcc -funroll-loops

	Run optimizations to make the compiler the smallest possible executable:
	gcc -Os

	Valid C++ source file names:
	.cpp, .cc, .cxx, .C

cmake - the CMake build system
	cmake -G "CodeBlocks - Unix Makefiles" -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug
	cmake -G "CodeBlocks - Unix Makefiles" -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release

as - the portable GNU assembler

ar - GNU ar - the GNU archiver. Archives for C libraries are created with this archiver.

nm - displays the symbol table of an executable

	Functions declared within the passed object file have the T flag.

strip - remove the symbol table off a compiled executable

ldd - shows if a program is statically compiled or uses outer libraries and lists
	  those libraries in such case

	get glibc version:
	ldd --version

ldconfig

	ldconfig -v - verbose mode (can be useful to list all the shared objects and
				  libraries on a system)

ld

cflow - analyzie C source files

objcopy

	How to compile image with ld and objcopy to include it as an extern variable:
	http://psydk.org/archives/2014-06-26-220-embed-a-binary-file-into-your-executable

objdump

	Display file header information:
	objdump -f file.o

	Display the dis-assembled output of executable sections:
	objdump -d file.o

	Display a complete binary hex dump of all sections:
	objdump -s file.o

vbindiff - ncurses-based tool for viewing hex dumps in binaries

TAU - open source multithreading profiler for C/C++, Fortran and JAVA
	https://www.cs.uoregon.edu/research/tau/home.php

ccache - tool for caching the compilation process of C/C++ software

	Speeding kernel compilation with ccache:
	http://linuxdeveloper.blogspot.bg/2012/05/using-ccache-to-speed-up-kernel.html

ccontrol - compilation controller

valgrind - C/C++ profiler and debugger

	valgrind --tool=callgrind ./program - the output file can then be reviewed
										  with GUI tools like kcachegrind

gcov - C/C++ code coverage tool that works with GCC

	We need to compile a binary with the following options to use gcov:
	gcc -fprofile-arcs -ftest-coverage source.c

	-ftest-coverage - collects how much each line of code is executed.
	-fprofile-arcs - collects information about each branch of the program

	lines marked with '######' are never executed.

	Outputs the following file extensions:
	.bb
	.bbg
	.da

gprof - C/C++ profiling tool that works with GCC

cpp - parser for C/C++ - show parser tokens for a C/C++/Objective-C file.

	Show all GCC defined macros (on an empty file):
	cpp -dM /dev/null

sysprof - Linux system profiler with GUI

strings - print the strings of printable characters - we can print only the strings off a binary file

	Get installed libcstd versions:
	strings /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libstdc++.so.6  | grep -i glib


hardening-check - check a binary for security hardening features

-- c/c++ programming tools --

chroot - run process in another directory

chrt - get and change real time attributes for a process

chattr - change file attributes on a Linux file system

	chattr -R - change file attributes recursively

lsattr - list file attributes on a Linux file system

	lsattr -R - list file attributes recursively in current directory
	lsattr -a - list attributes of all files in directory, including hidden ones
	lsattr -d - list attributes of directories

-- File Attributes --

(some of them)

A - the atime (accesstime, http://www.binarytides.com/linux-find-command-examples/) cannot be changed
a - can only be opened in append mode for writing
c - a file with this attribute is compressed by the kernel on the disk. Reading from it returns uncompressed data
i - cannot be modified, deleted or renamed, even from root
u - files with this attribute are saved after deletion and users can request its undeletion
-v - version

D - for directories only. Changes are written asynchronously to the disk
d - file cannot be backed up with dump journaling filesystem backup utility
j - ext3 filesystem specific option; all data is written to the ext3 journal before being written to the file itself;
	the ext3 filesystem should be mounted with the data=ordered or data=writeback options
s - file blocks are zeroed and written back to disk
S - similar to the sync mount option applied to a subset of files
T - top of directory hierarchy
t - for filesystems that support tail-merging
X - experimental functionality connected with compression, cannot be set with chattr
Z - experimental functionality connected with compression, cannot be set with chattr

-- file attributes --

sticky bit, suid, sgid explained

/dev/shm - shared memory implementation. Also known as tmpfs. It can be manipulated through /etc/fstab.

read - read a line from standard input

	It can be used in a shell script to store any command line input in a variable
	Cause read to timeout:
	read -t 3 - timeout after 3 seconds without input
	read -p 'Message: ' - print message before prompting for input

service - run a SystemV init script

	service --status-all

tasksel - a user interface for configuring the system to perform a specific task
	  It is used for installing desktop environments or the "laptop" task.

grep

	grep --color=auto - color the matched strings in the output
	grep --regex="thunder[[:alpha:]]" - use regular expressions (POSIX compliant)

	grep -A6 - display a number of lines AFTER a match
	grep -B6 - display a number of lines BEFORE a match
	grep -C6 - display a number of lines AFTER and BEFORE a match

	grep -c - count occurences
	grep -i - case insensitive mode
	grep -r - recurse into the current directory

	grep -v - show occurences that don't include string

	-P - force PCRE regex search
	-E - force ERE regex search
	-F - force the string to be read literally
	-w - grep for words

	Grep doesn't support the ? and + regex metacharacters!! Only the asterisk sign.
	< and > should be escaped when looked up

	grep lines containing multiple patterns:
	grep 'pattern1|pattern2' filename
	egrep -e pattern1 -e pattern2 filename

	grep -x - Select only those matches that exactly match the whole line.

	grep -F, --fixed-strings - Interpret PATTERN as a list of fixed strings, separated by  new-
       lines, any of which is to be matched.

	strip text file off files containing comments (the second grep is to filter
	blank lines from output):
	grep -v ^# config | grep .
	https://shapeshed.com/unix-grep/#how-to-list-line-numbers-for-matches

ack - grep alternative, written in Perl

	http://beyondgrep.com/
	cpan install App::Ack

vault - HashiCorp Vault CLI

	vault server -dev -dev-root-token-id=roottoken - start a dev server on port 8200
	export VAULT_ADDR='http://127.0.0.1:8200'
	vault status
	vault secrets - command for controlling secrets
	vault kv put secret/application mongopass=p4ssf0rm0ng0
	vault read secret/application

sed - stream editor

	http://www.theunixschool.com/2012/06/sed-25-examples-to-delete-line-or.html

egrep - grep with extended regular expressions support

	egrep -v "^#|^$" filename - remove comments and blank lines
	egrep  support the ? and + metacharacters, as opposed to grep.

fgrep, egrep and rgrep are the same binary executable

sed - stream editor

	http://www.theunixschool.com/2012/06/sed-25-examples-to-delete-line-or.html

-- USER MANAGEMENT --

gpasswd -a cvetomir docker - add already existing user to already existing group

usermod - modify a user account

	Add existing user to existing group:
	usermod -a -G <groupname> <username>

	Change user primary group:
	usermod -g <groupname> <username>

	Add user to more than one group:
	usermod -a -G ftp,admins,othergroup username

useradd

	add a new user and assign him to an already existing group:
	useradd -g <groupname> <username>

last - display the last users who started a login session

	reads information from the /var/log/wtmp binary file
	last reboot - get information about previous reboots

pwck - verify integrity of passwd files

	pwck /etc/passwd

pwuconv - convert to and from passwd files content

-- user management --

pwgen - generate random strings to be used in passwords

	pwgen -c - include atleast one capital
	pwgen 20 - generate strings of up to 20 symbols

fc - open the text editor set with VISUAL with the last command in the buffer

id [username] - displays UID, GID, groups

newgrp docker - make user aware of a group he was just added to

umask - remove permissions
	a file with 777 will have 700 after a umask 077 command

udisk - disk manager

modprobe - add and remove modules from the Linux kernel

	modprobe module - load module
	modprobe -l - lists loaded kernels (deprecated)
	modprobe -r - removes a module

	modprobe works with a file generated with depmod. This file is called
	system map. It is stored in /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/modules.dep

	modprobe --dump-modversions kernel/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/e1000/e1000.ko
	modprobe --show-modversions kernel/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/e1000/e1000.ko

modinfo

	modinfo path/to/kernel-module

kmod - modprobe is a symbolic link to /sbin/kmod

depmod - generate modules dependency files

nvidia-modprobe - nVidia kernel module loader and tool to create device nodes

getconf - get POSIX developer info

patch - apply patches to packages

	patch -p0 < toolname.patch	- p показва броя на директории, който ще махнем

watch - execute a program periodically watching the output

	watch -n1 'cat /proc/interrupts'

who
	who -r - display current runtime (init) levels

dkms - dynamic kernel module start

sysctl - configure kernel parameters at runtime

	sysctl -a - show all kernel variables
	sysctl -p - reload configuration
	sysctl -p /etc/sysctl.conf

	Get currently open file handlers:
	sysctl fs.file-nr

	Get limit for simultaneous open files:
	sysctl fs.file-max

systemctl - command line tool for managing systemd

	systemctl enable named.service
	systemctl restart sshd.service
	systemctl reload nginx.service - reload configuration file

	systemctl list-unit-files - list all active services
	systemctl is-enabled nginx.service - check if a service is enabled

	systemctl is-active nginx.service
	systemctl status service-name - get systemd status of a service

	systemctl list-dependencies named.service
	systemctl list-dependencies --all nginx.service - explain recursively
	systemctl list-sockets

	systemctl cat nginx.service - cat unit file

	systemctl reload-or-restart nginx.service - reloads configuration file if available or restarts service

	reload systemd configuration file:

		systemctl daemon-reload

journalctl

	journalctl -b - view logs only for current boot
	journalctl -k - view only kernel messages
	journalctl -k -b

	delete journal files:

	reduce them to 100M:
	journalctl --vacuum-size=100M

	remove those from the last two weeks:
	journalctl --vacuum-time=2weeks

timedatectl - a systemd tool for managing system date and time

bootctl - change /boot settings

stty - print and change terminal settings

dmidecode - reports information about your system's hardware as described in your system BIOS

	dmidecode -t bios -q - returns information about the BIOS
	dmidecode -t 16 - get information about maximum supported amount of RAM

/etc/network/interface - this file describes the network interfaces on your system

/etc/hosts
	/etc/init.d/network(ing) restart - it is recommended after editting the hosts file

/etc/security/limits.conf

	In this file we can set a variety of limits. For example, we can set the soft and hard
	limits for all users or on a per-user basis:

	www-data 	soft 	nofile 		10000
	www-data	hard	nofile		30000

	Prevent a fork bomb by limiting user processes:
	http://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/linux-limiting-user-process.html

	All limits that can be set:

	 - core - limits the core file size (KB)
	 - data - max data size (KB)
	 - fsize - maximum filesize (KB)
	 - memlock - max locked-in-memory address space (KB)
	 - nofile - max number of open files
	 - rss - max resident set size (KB)
	 - stack - max stack size (KB)
	 - cpu - max CPU time (MIN)
	 - nproc - max number of processes
	 - as - address space limit (KB)
	 - maxlogins - max number of logins for this user
	 - maxsyslogins - max number of logins on the system
	 - priority - the priority to run user process with
	 - locks - max number of file locks the user can hold
	 - sigpending - max number of pending signals
	 - msgqueue - max memory used by POSIX message queues (bytes)
	 - nice - max nice priority allowed to raise to values: [-20, 19]
	 - rtprio - max realtime priority
	 - chroot - change root to directory (Debian-specific)

pgrep - look up process id based on name

      pgrep -l $process-name - lists process names and ids starting with $process-name

multitail - tool with a split screen TUI for viewing real-time tails of multiple files

fg - starts stopped processes

bg - brings process to background

jobs - shows process status in the current session

How to get coredump of a running process:

	gdb --pid=123

	gcore $(pidof process-name)

ulimit - defines limits for a process (BASH specific)

	ulimit -l
	ulimit -a

	See hard and soft open file limits:
	ulimit -Hn - hard limit
	ulimit -Sn - soft limit

fuser - identify processes using files or sockets

	fuser -cu directory/

watch - watch processes

	watch -t - suppress timer

	Usually the cp command doesn't have a progress bar
			While we copy a large file, we can run watch du -h filename to watch the progress

	watch -n - specify time interval between command execution

	it can also be used as a timer:

	watch -n 1 " "
	watch -d - highlight differences in output
	watch -b - beep if the command has a non-zero exit
	watch -c - interpret color output
	watch -g - exit when the output is different
	watch -e - stops updates after error and the TUI can be exited after a key press
	watch -x - passes the command to exec

/etc/network/interfaces - Debian

/etc/sysconfig/network-scripts - CentOS

mysql - mysql client

	mysql -u username -p -h server.hostname.org -e "use database; select * from table"

	perform a MySQL dump for all the databases and tables without the events system table:
	mysqldump -u username -p --all-databases > all-databases.sql

	perform a MySQL dump for all the databases and tables with the mysql.events table:
	mysqldump -u username -p --all-databases --events > all-databases.sql

	perform a MySQL dump including stored routines (triggers are exported by default):
	http://www.ducea.com/2007/07/25/dumping-mysql-stored-procedures-functions-and-triggers/

pmm-admin - client program for the Percona Monitoring and Management server

pgrep - look up process id based on name

      pgrep -l $process-name - lists process names and ids starting with $process-name

crontab - set cronjobs

	http://cronchecker.net/

	crontab -e - edit personal crontab
	crontab -l - display personal crontab

	You can check if a cronjob was executed successfully in:
	/var/log/syslog

	Personal crontabs:
	/var/spool/cron/crontabs/

	NB!!!
	crontab -r - remove all contabs - key is close to 'e',
	so one should beware of this option and use crontab -l

logger - a CLI interface to the syslog functionality

logrotate

	logrotate -d /etc/logrotate/config - dry run a logrotate config
	logrotate -f /etc/logrotate/config - logrotate config file
	logrotate -v /etc/logrotate/config - verbose mode

run-parts

chkcrontab - verify crontab syntax(crontab linter)

	pip install chkcrontab

cksum - return checksum and the bites in a file

hexdump - dump a hex representation of a binary file

	hexdump -C /usr/bin/binary

