# use xargs with pgrep at the end
ps auxfwww | awk '{print $4" "$2}' | sort -n | tail -n 1 | awk '{print $2}' | xargs pgrep

xargs - echo stdin

	When used with a pipe it passes each line of output from the previous
	command to the command passed as argument to xargs.

	E.g.

	find -type d | xargs readlink -f - the absolute path of each dir
	found will be printed because each found dir with find will be
	passed to "readlink -f"

hdparm - get/set SATA/IDE device parameters

sdparm - access SCSI modes pages. Send simple SCSI commands.

mdadm - manage MD devices aka Linux software RAID

	CREATING A SOFTWARE RAID 5

	0. Mount 3 additional virtual VDA images that are all equal to 2GB. RAID 5 requires a minimum of three hard drives.

	00. check disks state with the fdisk partitioning utility

		sudo fdisk -l /dev/sda

	01. Create the software RAID 5 with the mdadm utility

		sudo mdadm --create /dev/md0 --chunk=64 --level=5 --raid-devices=3 /dev/sdc1 /dev/sdd1 /dev/sde1

		the --level option specifies the RAID level
		the --raid-devices specifies the number of devices included, followed by their block file representations in the /dev directory
		--chunk - specify chunk size in kibibytes

	02. Mount the new software RAID

		sudo mount /dev/md0 /mnt/disk1

	03. Format the new partition in ext4 journal file system

		sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/md0

RAID levels explained - http://www.prepressure.com/library/technology/raid
http://www.ducea.com/2009/03/08/mdadm-cheat-sheet/

Disable md* device used as swap:
https://mikebeach.org/2013/10/25/cannot-delete-a-raid-swap-partition-during-ubuntu-installation/

mkfs.ntfs

	By default mkfs.ntfs will zero write the device. This can
	take an additional amount of time.
	We can use the following option to skip this:
	mkfs.ntfs -f /dev/sdb1

ntfsclone - clone an NTFS file system

fdisk - partitioning tool

		m - help
		n - new partition
		primary, extended (p, e)
		l - list partition types
		d - delete partition
		w - write partition table to disk and exit
		q - quit
		p - print current partition table

sfdisk - partitioning tool
		 sfdisk -d /dev/sda - dump partition table
		 sfdisk -d /dev/sda | sfdisk /dev/sdb - copy the partition table to another device

mount - utility for mounting filesystems

	mount -a - mount all partitions listed in /etc/fstab

	mounting a shared folder in VirtualBox guest:
	mount -t vboxsf H_DRIVE /home/user/directory

fsck - check and repair a Linux filesystem
	/lost+found - fsck places corrupted files here after performing a check on a
	Linux/Unix filesystem, provided the FS is mounted on /
	If it is mounted on /var/log/mysql, it will place them in /var/log/mysql/lost+found

fsck.ext4

resize2fs - resize a file system

	We need to pass the resulting size of the file system, not the amount of space we would like to decrease or increase it with:
	resize2fs -p /dev/debian/debian_root 45G

e2fsck - check a Linux Ext2 / Ext3 / Ext4 file system

tune2fs - check and change file system settings

