dig - DNS lookup utility
	http://alvinalexander.com/linux-unix/dig-commands-examples-tcp-ip-mx-record-dns
	http://www.debianhelp.co.uk/dnsrecords.htm
	http://www.madboa.com/geek/dig/

	dig @8.8.8.8 abv.bg - perform a DNS query using a specific caching nameserver
		in this way we can validate a DNS record by performing a query with a
		DNS caching server different from our default to make sure of the
		domain name's credibility

	dig -x 12.34.56.78 - perform a DNS query for a PTR record

	NB!!! About how the DNS system works
	When querying the authoritative part of the DNS servers a DNS client asks
	for the NS records of a certain domain. After it receives this information
	it queries those nameservers for the records it needs to know (MX, A, AAAA etc).
	They are stored in the DNS zone for which the nameservers of the domain are in
	charge. A common mistake is to think that authoritative queries can give
	all the information in the DNS zone and the servers in the lower level of the
	DNS hierarchy only serve for caching this information.

domainname - returns the domain name pointed to (one of) the computer's TCP/IP address.

host - similar functionality to dig
	host -t ns sitedomain.com - display the authoritative name server for this domain name

	host -v hostname - enables DNS query verbose
host -m - set memory debugging flag

