ps

-- Linux Style --
-A - all processes (with tty)
-e - all processes (with tty)
-c - show scheduling class (aliased to policy, cls). Possible scheduling classes:

	 -   not reported
	 TS  SCHED_OTHER
	 FF  SCHED_FIFO
	 RR  SCHED_RR
	 B   SCHED_BATCH
	 ISO SCHED_ISO
	 IDL SCHED_IDLE
	 ?   unknown value

We can specify more than one argument, separated by coma or space to the following options:

-C - specify command name
-G - specify RGID name
-p - specify PID
-pid - specify PID
-ppid - specify PPID
-t - specify tty
-s - specify session id
--sid - specify session id

	ps -C chrome

-- BSD Style --

j - jobs
l - long output

a - all with tty, including the ones ran by another user
r - only running processes
T - all processes on this terminal
x - include processes without tty

Combinations:

ps -T -p $PID - return threads of a process

-- Process status code

    D    uninterruptible sleep (usually IO)
    R    running or runnable (on run queue)
    S    interruptible sleep (waiting for an event to complete)
    T    stopped, either by a job control signal or because it is being traced
    W    paging (not valid since the 2.6.xx kernel)
    X    dead (should never be seen)
    Z    defunct ("zombie") process, terminated but not reaped by its parent

    <    high-priority (not nice to other users)
    N    low-priority (nice to other users)
    L    has pages locked into memory (for real-time and custom IO)
    s    is a session leader
    l    is multi-threaded (using CLONE_THREAD, like NPTL pthreads do)
    +    is in the foreground process group


pstree - displays the processes with their belonging child processes and the parent process they are
	spawned from

locate - find files by name (part of find-utils)

unlink - remove symbolic(soft) link

http://www.binarytides.com/linux-find-command-examples/

Difference between ctime, mtime and atime:
http://www.linux-faqs.info/general/difference-between-mtime-ctime-and-atime

screen - GNU screen terminal multiplexer
	Ctrl + a + Shift + s - create a new horizontal window
	Ctrl + a + Tab - switch inbetween windows
	Ctrl + a + x - close session
	Ctrl + a + c - start a new BASH shell in the current window
	Ctrl + a + | - start a new vertical window (requires screen >= 4.1)
	Ctrl + d - terminate screen (different than the subsecuent combination!)
	Ctrl + a + d - detach screen session
	Ctrl + a + n - next window
	Ctrl + a + p - previous window
	Ctrl + a + A - rename current window
	Ctrl + a + :resize + number of lines - set lines in a window

	Scrolling in screen:
	Enter copy mode with Ctrl + A and [.
	Scroll with Ctrl + u and Ctrl + d.
	Press q to exit copy mode
	We can use / and ? for searching in the text.

	screen -ls - list screen sessions
	screen -r [session name] - reattach to session

	Ctrl + [ - enter copy mode
	Then scroll to previous and next lines through the following hotkeys:
	Ctrl - u
	Ctrl - b
	In copy mode we can search words with / and ? just like in vi.

screen - dump the virtual console output to stdout
		(usually found in /dev and starting with 'vcs')

mutt - console mail client
	Ctrl + D - mark email for deletion

ifconfig - configure a network interface

	MTU - maximum transmission units

	without arguements - lists enabled interfaces

	ifconfig -a
		lists all interfaces, even those disabled

	ifconfig eth0 up

	ifconfig eth0 down - the configuration for the networking interface is saved
						 We need to use this before changing the MAC address of
						 a networking interface

	ifconfig eth0 hw ether {macaddress} - changes the hardware address

	ifconfig ${Interface} mtu ${SIZE} up
	ifconfig eth1 mtu 9000 up

	Use promisquous mode:
	ifconfig eth0 promisc

	By default the NIC drops frames that it is intended to receive.
	In promiscuous mode it passes all the traffic that it receives to the CPU.

ip
	ip a a
	ip r l
	ip neigh - it is used to manage the ARP table
	ip addr show = ip addr list = ip a l = ip a s

	ip addr del

	how to blacklist an IP address or range(add a blackhole interface):

	ip route add blackhole 192.168.0.1/32

	ip route add 0/0 via 10.2.0.1 - adding a default gateway
	ip r a via 10.2.0.1 - adding a default gateway

	ip route replace 0/0 via 192.168.102.2

	ip rule list - parses /etc/iproute2/rt_tables

	ip route list table local/main/default

	Change MAC address:
	ip link set dev wlan0 down
	ip link set dev wlan0 address <new MAC address>
	ip link set dev wlan0 up

	ifconfig, ip and route - we directly communicate with the kernel using those commands

