	Pass existing shell environment variables of non-root user to root session:
	sudo -E bash

	Run a particular command as a certain user and see the output
	sudo -u nginx stat /home/cvetomir/workspaces/Common/project-management/

openssl - OpenSSL command line tool

	example:
	openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.key -out /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.crt

	Options explained:
	req -x509 - Specify the OpenSSL standard to be X.509.
	With the X.509 standard we specify that we would like to generate a self-signed certificate and not a
	certificate signing request as by default

	-nodes - skip passphrase. This is suitable for installing an SSL certificate on a webpage. Thus it will not
	require user intervention for entering the passphrase.

	-days 365 - validity period for the certificate

	-newkey rsa:2048 - specify cryptography algorythm.

	-keyout - output file for the private key

	-out - output file for the certificate

iptraf - TUI-based traffic monitor

sipcalc - calculate the network address and mask of an IP address

ipcalc - calculate IP addresses inbetween different numbering systems

mknod - make block and character special devices

