dpkg - Debian Package manager

	dpkg -i - install package
	dpkg -l - list all installed packages
	dpkg -L - list all files from an installed package
	dpkg --contents, dpkg -c - list package contents
	dpkg -s
	dpkg -p - purge - remove package with configuration files
	dpkg -r - remove package without configuration files
	dpkg -V - package verification

	dpkg --force-help - a list of actions we can force with dpkg

	Force install package without root in homedir:
	dpkg -i package.deb --force-not-root --root=$HOME

	Add architecture:
	dpkg --add-architecture i386

	Remove architecture:
	dpkg --remove-architecture i386

	Installing a package without root privileges in home
	directory:
	http://askubuntu.com/questions/339/how-can-i-install-a-package-without-root-access

	These are anonymously gathered statistics about the most used packages on a Debian system

dpkg-reconfigure popularity-contest - settings about the popularity contest
	It traces the popularity of various Debian packages.

dpkg-reconfigure - run configuration TUI menu used to configure a certain
		package upon installation

Debian packages are ar archives that contain three files:
- debian-binary
- control.tar.gz
- data.tar.gz

They can be extracted in the following way:

ar vx mypackage.deb
tar -xzvf data.tar.gz

Debian packages can be found in the following directory in a repository mirror:
$REPOSITORY_URL/debian/pool/
							contrib/
							main/
							non-free/

Packages states are recorded here:
/var/lib/dpkg/status

/etc/apt/trusted.pgp.d/
/etc/apt/sources.list
/etc/apt/sources.list.d/

A directive in the sources.list configuration file consists of:

type_of_repository URL_to_repository distribution repository_from_the_distribution

examples:

deb http://ftp.bg.debian.org/debian/ jessie main
deb-src http://ftp.bg.debian.org/debian/ jessie main

*.-dev - packages with such a postfix
		 are usually the development
		 header files for a package on a Debian-based system.

dlocate - apt-get/dpkg alternative (BASH script)

	Most dpkg options work with dlocate, e.g. -l and -L

	check which packages use a certain directory:
	dlocate /usr/lib/debug

unattended-upgrade - can perform only security upgrades

