java

	How to run a .jar archive:
	java -jar archive.jar

	Librariy to run Java programs as Unix services:
	https://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-daemon/jsvc.html

	How to install the JAVA compiler under CentOS/Fedora/RHEL:
	yum install java-devel

jenv

	version - show current Java version
	versions - list available versions
	enable-plugin - install a jenv plugin
		jenv enable-plugin maven - enable maven to read jenv configs
		jenv enable-plugin export - set JAVA_HOME through the export plugin
	local - set or show local java version for current directory
	global - set or show global java version for current directory
	exec - execute a specific command taking in consideration the specific Java env settings

jdb - Java debugger
jstack
-- java

-- User management

useradd

	Add a user with a specific home directory:
	useradd -d /home/testuser -m testuser

tar - the UNIX archiver

	tar -cvzf name.tgz subdir - create gzip tarball
	By default GNU tar uses 9th level of compression - the maximum level for gzip compression

	tar -cvpzf name.tar.gz dir/ - create tarball and preserver permissions
	tar --extract --file=crunchbang-home.tar.gz home/cvetomir/.vimrc - extract a certain file
		off the archive
	tar xzvf tarball.tar.gz dir/filename

	tar -zxvf name.tar.gz -C /tmp/ - extract to a certain directory
	tar -tf name.tar.gz - list files in an archive without extracting them

	tar overwrites metadata (ownership, permissions) of an already existing directory that is already full
	tar xf --no-overwrite-dir - perserve directory metadata of already existing directory

unzip

	unzip -l - list zip archive content

zip

	read file names from stdin:
	find . -name <name> -print | zip name.zip -@

ranlib - generate an index to speed up access to archives

cpio - copy files to and from archives

pax - archiving toolkit

strace - trace system calls and signals (issued by the signal system call) to track
		 interactions between a process and the operating system kernel

	strace -c - print an output as a table with the number of and percentage of
			 the used syscalls
	strace -o - write the strace output to a filename
	strace -f - trace child processes being span by the traced process

	Signals are a type of system call.

ltrace - trace the dynamic library calls which a process makes

expect - tool for testing and managing the output of interactive command-line programs

rev - reverse line of a file or files

nice - set process priority

smartctl - hard drive inspection tool suite

	https://kb.acronis.com/search/site/S.M.A.R.T.%20Attribute

	Smartctl disk health metrics:

	Raw_Read_Error_Rate - stores data related to the rate of hardware read errors that
						  occured when reading data from a disk surface.
	Spin_Up_Time - average time in seconds or miliseconds of spindle spinup from
				   0 rpm to fully operational.
	Start_Stop_Count - number of times the disk has been stopped and started

	Reallocated_Sector_Ct - reallocated sectors count. Reallocated sectors are 512
				   bytes in size. When the HDD finds a read/write/verification
				   error, it marks this sector as 'reallocated' and transfers the
				   data to a special reserved area (spare area). This is also
			       known as remapping. Reallocated sectors are also called remaps.
			       In modern disks all bad sectors are 'hidden' into remaps.

	Seek_Error_Rate - when the drive is over- or unser-shooting the correct
				   track when it moves the heads

	Power_On_Hours - hours in which the disk has been in power-on state

	Spin_Retry_Count - count of retry of spin start attempts.

	Power_Cycle_Count - full hard disk power on/off cycles.

	Reported_Uncorrect - errors that cannot be recovered using hardware correcting codes

	High_Fly_Writes (Seagate, Western Digital) - indicates when a recording head
				  is flying outside its normal operating range

	Airflow_Temperature_Cel - air temperature of HDD

	Temperature_Celsius - temperature in Celsius

	Hardware_ECC_Recovered - timedifference between ECC-corrected errors

	Current_Pending_Sector

	Offline_Uncorrectable - Offline_Uncorrectable is the number of sectors
				  that the drive has attempted to correct itself, but failed.
	http://daemon-notes.com/articles/system/smartmontools/offline-uncorrectable

	UDMA_CRC_Error_Count

	Multi_Zone_Error_Rate - the count of errors found when writing a sector

	Data_Address_Mark_Errs - the number of invalid data marks

	get basic information about disk and check if it does support S.M.A.R.T
	smartctl -i /dev/sda

	Enable smart for a device:
	smartctl -s on /dev/sda

	Get the time needed to perform different types of tests:
	smartctl -c /dev/sda
	smartctl --capabilities /dev/sda

	Start short test:
	smartctl -t short /dev/sda
	smartctl -t long /dev/sda
	smartctl -t conveyance /dev/sda

	View test results:
	smartctl -l selftest /dev/sda

	Display info by specifying disk type:
	smartctl -a -d ata /dev/sda (this also works for IDE drives in new
		kernels that are being run through the SCSI stack and show up as
		/dev/sda

	Get overral health status:
	smartctl -H /dev/sda

	GSmartControl - Linux GUI to S.M.A.R.T.

	Directories (on a Debian-based system):
	/etc/smartctl.conf
	/etc/smartmontools/run.d/
	/usr/share/smartmontools/smartd-runner
	/etc/default/smartmontools - from here we can enable smartd
		To enable it add the following line:
		start_smartd=yes
	DB Header:
	/var/lib/smartmontools/drivedb/drivedb.h

renice - set process priority

aspell - command line spell checker

	aspell -c letter.txt
	aspell dump dicts - list installed dictionaries for current locale
	apt-get install aspell-en - to install English dictionaries

Wireless configuration on a laptop with Linux:
	http://svobodnaplaneta.com/story/4025

Display number of inodes in the current directory:
echo "Inode usage for: $(pwd)" ; for d in `find -maxdepth 1 -type d |cut -d\/ -f2 |grep -xv . |sort`; do c=$(find $d |wc -l) ;
 printf "$c\t\t- $d\n" ; done ; printf "Total: \t\t$(find $(pwd) | wc -l)\n"

htop
	difference between top and htop: top displays RAM usage including the cached RAM.
				htop excludes it.

atop - AT's server monitoring tool

GRUB

	Full GRUB 2 tutorial:
	http://www.dedoimedo.com/computers/grub-2.html

	Creating a bootable Windows USB under Linux:
	http://onetransistor.blogspot.bg/2014/09/make-bootable-windows-usb-from-ubuntu.html
	http://askubuntu.com/questions/289559/how-can-i-create-a-windows-bootable-usb-stick-using-ubuntu

	The USB should have a bootable flag and the NTFS flag from cfdisk (7th option).
	We need to install an ntfs file system on it.
	Then windows iso can be mounted with mount -o loop and the files can be copied to the USB afterwards.
	After that GRUB 2 can be installed on the USB for it to boot.
	The grub entry should be added to $WIN_USB/boot/grub/grub.cfg

	Generate an encrypted string to add an encrypted password for password protected boot in GRUB:
	grub-mkpasswd-pbkdf2

	Login with root on a machine with unsecure boot loader.
	Press 'e' in the GRUB menu. Select kernel and press 'e' again.

	update-grub/update-grub2 (only on Debian/Ubuntu) - can be used to automatically greate new grub entries for new kernels

	HDD naming convention:
	https://www.gnu.org/software/grub/manual/html_node/Naming-convention.html

VirtualBox

	Arch Linux:
	http://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/88081/arch-linux-on-virtualbox-internet-connection-issue-on-virtualbox
	http://forums.whirlpool.net.au/archive/1104558

	VirtualBox Arch Linux error and fix:
	piix4_smbus 0000.00.07.0: SMBus base address uninitialized - upgrade bios or use force_addr=0xaddr
	echo blacklist i2c_piix4 >> /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf

	How to use shared folders with Guest VirtualBox:
			- Devices -> install guest additions - mount the Virtualbox guest additions cdrom on /media/cdrom
			- navigate to /media/cdrom
			- run autorun.sh and install the needed drivers
			- mount the directory you've shared with the following command run as root:
				mount -t vboxsf -o rw,exec,uid=1000,gid=1000,dev directory-name /path/to/guest/location

	How to open TTY in a VirtualBox Linux instance (similar to Ctrl+Alt+F{1..12} on a host Linux machine)

	Right Ctrl + F1/F2/F3 etc.

	In case of UUID already registered error:
	VBoxManage internalcommands sethduuid box.vdi

	In case of UUID mismatch error:
	File -> Virtual Media Manager -> Select Disk -> Right click and Release/Remove
	-> Re-add disk to Box

qemu

	qemu-system-i386 -cdrom os-image.iso
	qemu-system-i386 -hda dsl.img -cdrom os-image.iso -boot d

	Create image:
	qemu-img create dsl.img 2G

	Test image:
	qemu-img info sample.vmdk

	qemu-img -incoming

	Boot from image:
	qemu-system-i386 -hda dsl.img

	Emulate a specific CPU:
	qemu-system-i386 -cpu n270 - emulate Intel Atom
	qemu-system-i386 -cpu help - list available architectures

	Specify amount of RAM for instance:
	qemu -m 256 -hda winxp.img -cdrom winxpsp2.iso -boot d

	Usage of additional images in QEMU:
	qemu -m 256 -hda winxp.img -hdb pagefile.img -hdc testdata.img -hdd tempfiles.img -kernel-kqem
	NB!!!
	We cannot use the -cdrom option when using -hdc

	qemu-io - tool for changing I/O path

	qemu-user - run a binary compiled for another architecture on the same system

	Drop into QEMU console:
	Ctrl + Alt + 2

	Return to virtual machine:
	Ctrl + Alt + 1

	To open new tty in guest machine, you can use the following in QEMU console:
	sendkey ctrl-alt-f1

	Boot a live USB via QEMU:
	http://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/37779/how-do-i-boot-from-a-liveusb-using-qemu-kvm
	qemu-system-x86_64 -hda /dev/sda

VMware Player

	Run installation script with EULA:
	(as root) ./VMware-edition-version.release.architecture.bundle --eulas-agreed

	compile and install the needed modules after VMPlayer/VMware Workstation installation:
