All protocols declared in RFC:
https://www.rfc-editor.org/materials/abbrev.expansion.txt

ARP - Address Resolution Protocol, usually the software for the manipulation of those addresses is
      called arp in most operating systems. It uses broadcast to find the MAC addresses.
APIPA - Automatic Private Internet Protocol Addressing - another way to automatically asign IP addresses, besides DHCP
	    Only used by Microsoft OSs. Only assigns IP addresses in the range of 169.254.0.1 - 169.254.255.255
AES - Advanced Encryption Standard - hardware encryption standard
	http://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/how-to-find-out-aes-ni-advanced-encryption-enabled-on-linux-system/
	Extension for the x86/x86_64 instruction set that provides hardware speed improvement for software using the
	AES algorythm (openssl, ssh, openvpn, *nix full disk encryption)
NTP - Network Time Protocol
NNTP - Network News Transfer Protocol
NIC - Netrwork interface controller (also network interface card, network adapter, LAN adapter,
	  physical network interface)
TUN - network tunnel - virtual kernel layer 3 network device. Used by VPN technology. Works with layer 3 protocols (e.g. IP packets).
TAP - network tap - virtual kernel layer 2 (link layer) network device. Used by VPN technology.
PDU - Protocol Data Unit - units into which data is separated for a certain protocol to work with
SNMP - Simple Network Management Protocol
STP - Staning-Tree Protocol
SIP - Session Initiation Protocol
CRT - Combined Rlogin And Telnet
ELF - Executable and Linking Format
COFF - Common Object File Format
LSB - Least Significant Byte
MSB - Most Significant Byte
	LSB and MSB are respectively known as little endiand and big endian.	

CVE - Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures
PPP - 	Point to Point Protocol
PPTP - Point to Point Tunneling Protocol
POE - Power over Ethernet
STP - shielded twisted pairs
VoIP - Voice over IP
UPnP - Universal Plug and Play
UPS - Uninterruptable Power supply
SMB - Server Message Block
SFP - Small Form-factor Pluggable
BGP - Border Gateway Protocol
IGMP - Internet Group Management Protocol - communication layer protocol for creating multicast groups
IPMI - Intelligent Platform Management Interface (Supermicro's KVM)
IOPS - Input/Output Operations Per Second
Telnet - protocol for terminal emulation for remote terminal connection
	 	 It can be used for remote manipulation of routers. Connection is not encrypted.
DWDM - 	Dense Wavelength Division Multiplexing - an optical technology used to increase bandwidth over
	existing fiber optic backbones.
SFP -
DMZ - Demilitarized zone - a public network in which an organization's external services are exposed
VRM - Voltage Regular Module
NIS - Network Information Service

SMP - Symmetric multi-processing support
	  Multicore is a sub-set of SMP
PIIX - PCI IDE ISA Xcelerator
PAE - Physical Address extension - CPU functionality, which allows to allocate more than 4GB of
	  memory on a 32 bit system
VME - Intel support for Virtual 8086 mode
VMX - Intel CPU flag for VT - needed to compile kernel for adding virtualization support
PXE - Preboot Execution Environment
PGA - Pin Grid Array - the pins on a processor or a motherboard
SCGI - Simple CGI protocol
XSL - XSL attack - Extended Sparse Linearization
SDCH - Shared Dictionary Compression for HTTP - compression algorithm, created by Google for Chrome
IDE - Integrated Drive Electronics
AHCI
ACPI
CMOS - Complementary Metal-Oxide Semiconductor - contains available hard disks, system time(UTC) and
	   boot priorities of disks

Network interface bonding, port trunking, channel bonding, link aggregation, NIC teaming -
combination of multiple network connecitons into a single
logical network interface

UNIX = UNIplexed Information and Computing Service

tty - native terminal device - either hardware or kernel emulated device
pty (pseudo terminal device) - terminal device emulated by another program (e.g.
	xterm, screen, ssh)
pts (pseudo terminal slave) - slave of pty.

SOLID principles

SOAP - Simple Object Access Protocol
DTD - Document Table Definition - in XML formatting describes how the document is formatted
RSS - Rich Site Summary

PEP - Python Enhancement Proposals

WDDX - A XML format for storing sessions, most famous for being used by PHP
SASL - Simple Authentication and Security Layer - authentication layer for application layer protocols
TTFB - Time To First Byte - the time since an HTTP request is sent by the browser
	   until the first byte from the web page is received.
RTT - Round-trip delay time

FFI - Foreign Function Interface
ABI - Application Binary Interface
Mutex - Mutual Exclusion

CHS - Cylinder, Head, Sector addressing
LBA - Linear Block addressing
PBR - Partition Boot record - stored in first sector
	  of bootable partition

DLL - Dynamic-Link Libraries

SAN - Storage Area Network
NAT - Network Attached Storage

PCI-DSS - Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard

